The paper discusses decision-making in complex partially observable stochastic games, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science. The use of Monte-Carlo sampling techniques suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and game theory (cs.GT). The mention of theoretical convergence guarantees and the comparison of different algorithms suggests a focus on machine learning (cs.LG) and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the application of these techniques to complex systems suggests a focus on systems and control (cs.SY).
